HAVING your land back after fighting for years is a great feeling. And no one knows that feeling better than the community of Luka, near Rustenburg, North West. The community was caught up in a 10-year long fight in the Mahikeng High Court with the Bafokeng tribal office over land. On 9 March, the Mahikeng High Court ruled in their favour. The community was overjoyed at the ruling and went on a peaceful march to celebrate its victory.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The community formed the Bafokeng Land Buyers Association to protect their rights and fight against the tribal office. The association’s secretary, Othusitse Rapoo, said: “Since 2008 we have been in and out of court to ensure that our people’s rights regarding land issue are not violated. After years of going to trial, finally judgment was given and the victory favoured us.”